 phases with density-independent lattice constants. We use molecular dynamics simulations in two dimensions to demonstrate that, through a judicious design of an isotropic pair potential, one can control the ordering of the clusters and generate a variety of phases, including decagonal and dodecagonal quasicrystals. Our results confirm analytical predictions based on a mean-field approximation, providing insight into the stabilization of quasicrystals in soft macromolecular systems, and suggesting a practical approach for their controlled self-assembly in laboratory realizations using synthesized soft-matter particles. Â© 2014 American Physical Society.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84907337173" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84907337173&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84907337173%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60025778" id="60025778"><affilname>University Michigan Ann Arbor</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60031581" id="60031581"><affilname>California Institute of Technology</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60005681" id="60005681"><affilname>Tel Aviv University</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="45661027900" seq="1"><ce:initials>K.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Barkan K.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Barkan</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Kobi</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>K.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Barkan K.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Barkan</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Kobi</ce:given-name></preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/45661027900</author-url><affiliation href="http://a